{"TopicId":190028,"ForumId":44,"TopicTitle":"Inside The 24/7 Search For Another Habitable Planet Within 100 Light Years Of Earth","CreatedByName":"caballerodiez","CreatedById":190290,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-11-26T23:08:51Z","PageNum":1,"Articles":[{"CreatedByName":"caballerodiez","CreatedById":190290,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-11-26T23:08:52Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp style=\u0022color:#222222;font-size:15px;\u0022\u003E\nHi,\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022color:#222222;font-size:15px;\u0022\u003E\nForbes just published an article about the Habitable Exoplanet Hunting Project:\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022color:#222222;font-size:15px;\u0022\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://www.forbes.com/sites/jamiecartereurope/2019/11/25/inside-the-247-search-for-another-habitable-planet-within-100-light-years-of-earth/#149fbf103442\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttp://www.forbes.com/sites/jamiecartereurope/2019/11/25/inside-the-247-search-for-another-habitable-planet-within-100-light-years-of-earth/#149fbf103442\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022color:#222222;font-size:15px;\u0022\u003E\nI hope you find it interesting!\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022color:#222222;font-size:15px;\u0022\u003E\nWe welcome any type of observatory to join us.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022color:#222222;font-size:15px;\u0022\u003E\nCheers!\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Gargamel","CreatedById":64714,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-11-27T05:57:06Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nMoved to S\u0026amp;S\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Mitchz95","CreatedById":82292,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-11-27T14:49:20Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\nQuote\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EWhy the focus on G, K and M-type stars? \u00A0\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u201CThey\u2019re the stars that are most likely to host exoplanets with water on their surface because they don\u2019t flare,\u201D says Caballero. \u201CIf a star flares, it can damage the atmosphere of the exoplanets.\u201D\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nM-types are flare stars, aren\u0027t they?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222019-11-27T14:49:32Z\u0022 title=\u002211/27/2019 02:49  PM\u0022 data-short=\u00224 yr\u0022\u003ENovember 27, 2019\u003C/time\u003E by Mitchz95\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Wjolcz","CreatedById":39636,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-11-27T17:17:50Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00223710389\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022190028\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221574866160\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u002282292\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022Mitchz95\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n2 hours ago, Mitchz95 said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nM-types are flare stars, aren\u0027t they?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nYep. Funnily, there are better stars than M-types and the Sun that could potentially have Earth-like planets and they are the K-types.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"RealKerbal3x","CreatedById":183830,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-11-28T06:43:15Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nSo we\u2019re looking for a class-M planet, right? \u003Cspan\u003E\u003Cimg alt=\u0022:P\u0022 data-emoticon=\u0022\u0022 src=\u0022//kerbal-forum-uploads.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/emoticons/default_k_tongue.gif\u0022 title=\u0022:P\u0022\u003E\u003C/span\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Spaceception","CreatedById":152800,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-11-30T19:23:10Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00223710389\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022190028\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221574866160\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u002282292\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022Mitchz95\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\nOn 11/27/2019 at 9:49 AM, Mitchz95 said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nM-types are flare stars, aren\u0027t they?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nMany are. I think some can be fairly calm... for a red dwarf at least.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nRegardless, I think it\u0027s a good idea to look for life in places we \u003Cem\u003Edon\u0027t \u003C/em\u003Eexpect it. If it can survive there, it can survive almost anywhere.\u003Cbr\u003E\nThen the immediate problem after that is around the Fermi paradox, and perhaps the great filters.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"}]}